2. NOSQL vs SQL
Side-by-Side Comparison
┌──────────────────────┬─────────────────────┬──────────────────────┐
│ Aspect               │ SQL (Relational)    │ NoSQL                │
├──────────────────────┼─────────────────────┼──────────────────────┤
│ Data Structure       │ Tables (rows)       │ Documents, Keys      │
│ Schema               │ Fixed, Predefined   │ Flexible, Dynamic    │
│ Joins                │ YES (powerful)      │ NO (embed data)      │
│ Scaling              │ Vertical (harder)   │ Horizontal (easy)    │
│ Transactions         │ Strong (ACID)       │ Weak (BASE)          │
│ Query Language       │ SQL                 │ Various              │
│ Data Redundancy      │ Normalized          │ Denormalized         │
│ Consistency          │ Strong              │ Eventual             │
│ Use Case             │ Structured data     │ Unstructured data    │
│ Examples             │ MySQL, PostgreSQL   │ MongoDB, Redis       │
└──────────────────────┴─────────────────────┴──────────────────────┘

Example: User with Addresses

SQL (Multiple tables):
┌──────────────┐         ┌──────────────┐
│ USERS        │         │ ADDRESSES    │
├──────────────┤         ├──────────────┤
│ id: 1        │────────→│ user_id: 1   │
│ name: Alice  │  JOIN   │ street: Main │
│ email: ...   │         │ city: NYC    │
└──────────────┘         └──────────────┘

Need JOIN to get user with addresses

NoSQL (Single document):
{
  "_id": 1,
  "name": "Alice",
  "email": "alice@test.com",
  "addresses": [        ← Embedded
    {
      "street": "Main St",
      "city": "NYC"
    },
    {
      "street": "2nd Ave",
      "city": "Boston"
    }
  ]
}

All data in one document

3. TYPES OF NOSQL DATABASES
Type 1: Document Databases
WHAT: Store data as documents (JSON-like)

EXAMPLE:
{
  "_id": ObjectId,
  "name": "Alice",
  "age": 25,
  "skills": ["JavaScript", "Node.js"],
  "profile": {
    "bio": "Developer",
    "followers": 1000
  }
}

BEST FOR:
├─ User profiles
├─ Content management
├─ Product catalogs
└─ Flexible data

POPULAR: MongoDB, CouchDB, Firebase

Type 2: Key-Value Stores
WHAT: Store data as key-value pairs

EXAMPLE:
key: "user:1"
value: {name: "Alice", email: "alice@test.com"}

key: "cache:homepage"
value: "<html>...</html>"

STRUCTURE:
┌─────────────────────────────────────┐
│ KEY          │ VALUE               │
├──────────────┼─────────────────────┤
│ user:1       │ {name: Alice, ...}  │
│ post:100     │ {title: Hello, ...} │
│ token:abc123 │ {user_id: 1, ...}   │
│ cache:page1  │ "<html>..."         │
└─────────────────────────────────────┘

BEST FOR:
├─ Caching
├─ Sessions
├─ Real-time data
├─ Leaderboards
└─ Rate limiting

POPULAR: Redis, Memcached, DynamoDB

Type 3: Column-Family Databases
WHAT: Store data by columns instead of rows

TRADITIONAL (Row-based):
┌────────┬────────┬────────┐
│ Name   │ Email  │ Age    │
├────────┼────────┼────────┤
│ Alice  │ alice@ │ 25     │
│ Bob    │ bob@   │ 30     │
└────────┴────────┴────────┘

COLUMN-FAMILY (Column-based):
Name Column:     Email Column:      Age Column:
├─ Alice         ├─ alice@test.com   ├─ 25
├─ Bob           ├─ bob@test.com     ├─ 30
└─ Charlie       └─ charlie@test.com └─ 35

Better for: Analyzing one column across all rows

BEST FOR:
├─ Time-series data
├─ Analytics
├─ Large-scale data
├─ Aggregations
└─ Data warehouses

POPULAR: Cassandra, HBase

Type 4: Graph Databases
WHAT: Store data as nodes (vertices) and relationships (edges)

EXAMPLE - Social Network:

    Alice ──friend──→ Bob
     ↑                 ↓
     │                 │
   follows          follows
     │                 │
     └─→ Tech Blog ←──┘

STRUCTURE:
Nodes:
├─ Alice (Person)
├─ Bob (Person)
└─ Tech Blog (Page)

Relationships:
├─ Alice --friend--> Bob
├─ Alice --follows--> Tech Blog
└─ Bob --follows--> Tech Blog

QUERY EXAMPLE:
"Find friends of Alice who also follow Tech Blog"

BEST FOR:
├─ Social networks
├─ Recommendations
├─ Knowledge graphs
├─ Fraud detection
└─ Navigation

POPULAR: Neo4j, Amazon Neptune

