4. SCHEMA-LESS / FLEXIBLE SCHEMA
What is Schema?
SCHEMA = Rules about what data structure should look like

SQL SCHEMA (Fixed):
┌─────────────────────────────────────┐
│ CREATE TABLE users (               │
│   id INT PRIMARY KEY,              │
│   name VARCHAR(100),               │
│   email VARCHAR(100),              │
│   age INT                          │
│ )                                  │
└─────────────────────────────────────┘

Every user MUST have: id, name, email, age
Can't add new fields easily

NOSQL SCHEMA (Flexible):
{
  "name": "Alice",
  "email": "alice@test.com",
  "age": 25,
  "phone": "+1234567890"  ← Added without changing schema
}

{
  "name": "Bob",
  "email": "bob@test.com"  ← No age or phone field
}

Each document can have different fields
Why Flexible Schema is Good
Scenario: Building a user profile system

Week 1: Users have name, email
{
  "name": "Alice",
  "email": "alice@test.com"
}

Week 2: Add age
{
  "name": "Alice",
  "email": "alice@test.com",
  "age": 25
}

Week 3: Add phone
{
  "name": "Alice",
  "email": "alice@test.com",
  "age": 25,
  "phone": "+1234567890"
}

Week 4: Add social links
{
  "name": "Alice",
  "email": "alice@test.com",
  "age": 25,
  "phone": "+1234567890",
  "social": {
    "twitter": "@alice",
    "github": "alice-dev"
  }
}

In SQL: ALTER TABLE users ADD COLUMN... (slow, risky)
In NoSQL: Just add field (instant, safe)

