8. DENORMALIZATION
What is Normalization vs Denormalization?
NORMALIZATION (SQL approach):
Eliminate data duplication by splitting into tables

USER TABLE:
┌────┬───────────┐
│ id │ name      │
├────┼───────────┤
│ 1  │ Alice     │
│ 2  │ Bob       │
└────┴───────────┘

ADDRESS TABLE:
┌────┬─────────────┬────────────┬──────────┐
│ id │ user_id     │ street     │ city     │
├────┼─────────────┼────────────┼──────────┤
│ 1  │ 1           │ Main St    │ NYC      │
│ 2  │ 1           │ 2nd Ave    │ Boston   │
│ 3  │ 2           │ Oak Ln     │ LA       │
└────┴─────────────┴────────────┴──────────┘

Pro: No data duplication
Con: Need JOINs to get complete data

DENORMALIZATION (NoSQL approach):
Duplicate data in single document for fast access

{
  "_id": 1,
  "name": "Alice",
  "addresses": [
    { "street": "Main St", "city": "NYC" },
    { "street": "2nd Ave", "city": "Boston" }
  ]
}

{
  "_id": 2,
  "name": "Bob",
  "addresses": [
    { "street": "Oak Ln", "city": "LA" }
  ]
}

Pro: Fast access, no JOINs needed
Con: Data duplication, harder to update

9. INDEXING
What is an Index?
INDEX = Speed up data retrieval (like book index)

BOOK WITHOUT INDEX:
Reading entire book to find topic = SLOW ❌

BOOK WITH INDEX:
Page 5: "Arrays"
Page 12: "Objects"
Page 18: "Functions"

Look in index, jump to page = FAST ✅

DATABASE WITHOUT INDEX:
Query: Find user with email "alice@test.com"
Action: Check every document in collection = SLOW

DATABASE WITH INDEX:
Create index on email field
Query: Find user with email "alice@test.com"
Action: Look in email index, direct access = FAST
Types of Indexes
1. SINGLE FIELD INDEX
   Create index on one field
   
   CREATE INDEX ON users.email
   
   Good for: Filtering by one field
   Example: Find user by email

2. COMPOUND INDEX
   Create index on multiple fields
   
   CREATE INDEX ON users(country, city)
   
   Good for: Filtering by multiple fields
   Example: Find users in USA, Texas

3. TEXT INDEX
   Create index for text search
   
   CREATE TEXT INDEX ON articles.content
   
   Good for: Full-text search
   Example: Search articles for keyword

4. GEOSPATIAL INDEX
   Create index for location data
   
   CREATE GEOSPATIAL INDEX ON stores.location
   
   Good for: Location-based queries
   Example: Find stores near me

10. CAP THEOREM
The Three Properties
CONSISTENCY (C)
├─ All users see same data
├─ If Alice updates profile, Bob sees update immediately
├─ Strong guarantee
└─ Trade-off: Slower updates

Example:
Alice updates profile
├─ Write to Database 1 ✓
├─ Write to Database 2 ✓
├─ Write to Database 3 ✓
└─ All consistent

AVAILABILITY (A)
├─ System always responds
├─ Even if some servers are down
├─ No downtime
└─ Trade-off: Might see old data

Example:
Database 1 goes down
├─ System routes to Database 2
├─ Response: ✓ Still available
└─ Users see results

PARTITION TOLERANCE (P)
├─ System works even if network splits
├─ Servers can't communicate
├─ System continues functioning
└─ Trade-off: Data might be inconsistent

Example:
Network splits: East Coast ↔ West Coast
├─ East Coast servers isolated
├─ West Coast servers isolated
├─ Both continue working
└─ Data gets out of sync
CAP Theorem Rule
You can have only 2 of 3 properties

┌──────────────────────────────────────┐
│     CP (Consistency + Partition)     │
├──────────────────────────────────────┤
│ • Strong consistency                 │
│ • Works when network splits          │
│ • NOT always available               │
│ Example: Traditional SQL, MongoDB    │
└──────────────────────────────────────┘

┌──────────────────────────────────────┐
│     AP (Availability + Partition)    │
├──────────────────────────────────────┤
│ • Always available                   │
│ • Works when network splits          │
│ • WEAK consistency (eventual)        │
│ Example: Cassandra, DynamoDB        │
└──────────────────────────────────────┘

┌──────────────────────────────────────┐
│     CA (Consistency + Availability)  │
├──────────────────────────────────────┤
│ • Always consistent                  │
│ • Always available                   │
│ • NOT partition tolerant             │
│ • Fails if network splits            │
│ Example: Traditional SQL (single)    │
└──────────────────────────────────────┘

11. CONSISTENCY MODELS
Strong Consistency
STRONG CONSISTENCY = Everyone sees same data immediately

Timeline:
Alice writes: name = "Alice"
    ↓
Update Database
    ↓
Charlie reads immediately
    ↓
Charlie sees: name = "Alice" ✓

Guarantee: If you write, next read is fresh

Pros: ✓ No confusion
Cons: ✗ Slower, harder to scale
Used: SQL, MongoDB

Eventual Consistency
EVENTUAL CONSISTENCY = Data syncs after short delay

Timeline:
Alice writes: name = "Alice"
    ↓
Update Database 1
    ↓
Syncing to Database 2, 3, 4...
    ↓
Charlie reads from Database 2
    ├─ Might see old data (update not synced yet)
    ↓
Wait 100ms
    ├─ Database 2 synced
    ↓
Charlie reads again
    ├─ Now sees: name = "Alice" ✓

Guarantee: Eventually everyone sees latest data

Pros: ✓ Faster, easier to scale
Cons: ✗ Temporary inconsistency
Used: Cassandra, DynamoDB, Redis

12. REPLICATION
Master-Slave Replication
ONE MASTER (writes) → MANY SLAVES (read copies)

MASTER:
┌─────────────────────────────────────┐
│ Write Operations                    │
├─────────────────────────────────────┤
│ Create user                         │
│ Update profile                      │
│ Delete post                         │
└──────────────┬──────────────────────┘
               │
        ┌──────┴──────┬──────────┐
        ↓             ↓          ↓
    SLAVE 1      SLAVE 2   SLAVE 3
    (Read)       (Read)    (Read)
    
Replication:
Master → Slave 1 ✓
Master → Slave 2 ✓
Master → Slave 3 ✓

Reads distributed, Writes centralized

Example: MySQL, PostgreSQL

Master-Master Replication
MULTIPLE MASTERS (both write and replicate)

MASTER 1 ↔ MASTER 2 ↔ MASTER 3

Both can:
├─ Accept writes
└─ Replicate to others

Advantage: ✓ High availability
Disadvantage: ✗ Conflict resolution needed

Example: Cassandra, DynamoDB

13. SHARDING
What is Sharding?
SHARDING = Split data across multiple servers

NO SHARDING:
┌──────────────────────────────────┐
│ Database                         │
├──────────────────────────────────┤
│ Users: 1-1,000,000               │
│ Posts: 1-100,000,000             │
│ Comments: 1-500,000,000          │
│ Size: 1 TB                       │
└──────────────────────────────────┘

Problem: One server handles everything ❌

SHARDING:
┌──────────────────┐  ┌──────────────────┐  ┌──────────────────┐
│ Shard 1          │  │ Shard 2          │  │ Shard 3          │
├──────────────────┤  ├──────────────────┤  ├──────────────────┤
│ Users: 1-333k    │  │ Users: 333k-666k │  │ Users: 666k-1M   │
│ 300 GB           │  │ 300 GB           │  │ 300 GB           │
└──────────────────┘  └──────────────────┘  └──────────────────┘

Data split across servers ✓

Sharding Key: Field used to determine shard
Example: user_id

user_id = 1 → Shard 1
user_id = 500000 → Shard 2
user_id = 1000000 → Shard 3

14. CRUD OPERATIONS
CREATE (INSERT)
INSERT = Add new document to collection

MONGODB SYNTAX:
db.users.insertOne({
  name: "Alice",
  email: "alice@test.com",
  age: 25
})

RESULT:
{
  "acknowledged": true,
  "insertedId": ObjectId("507f1f77bcf86cd799439011")
}

What happens:
1. Create new document
2. Generate unique ID
3. Add to collection
4. Return ID

READ (FIND)
READ = Retrieve documents from collection

FIND ALL:
db.users.find()

Result:
[
  { _id: 1, name: "Alice", age: 25 },
  { _id: 2, name: "Bob", age: 30 },
  { _id: 3, name: "Charlie", age: 35 }
]

FIND SPECIFIC:
db.users.findOne({ name: "Alice" })

Result:
{ _id: 1, name: "Alice", age: 25 }

FIND WITH FILTER:
db.users.find({ age: { $gt: 25 } })

Result:
[
  { _id: 2, name: "Bob", age: 30 },
  { _id: 3, name: "Charlie", age: 35 }
]

UPDATE
UPDATE = Modify existing document

BASIC UPDATE:
db.users.updateOne(
  { _id: 1 },
  { $set: { age: 26 } }
)

Before:
{ _id: 1, name: "Alice", age: 25 }

After:
{ _id: 1, name: "Alice", age: 26 }

UPDATE MULTIPLE:
db.users.updateMany(
  { age: { $lt: 30 } },
  { $set: { status: "junior" } }
)

Updates all users younger than 30

OPERATORS:
$set:     Set field value
$inc:     Increment by number
$push:    Add to array
$pull:    Remove from array
$unset:   Remove field

DELETE
DELETE = Remove document from collection

DELETE ONE:
db.users.deleteOne({ _id: 1 })

Deletes one document

DELETE MANY:
db.users.deleteMany({ age: { $gt: 50 } })

Deletes all users older than 50

DELETE ALL:
db.users.deleteMany({})

Deletes entire collection

15. TRANSACTIONS
What are Transactions?
TRANSACTION = Multiple operations as single unit

ACID Properties:
A - Atomicity (all or nothing)
C - Consistency (valid state)
I - Isolation (no interference)
D - Durability (persists after commit)

EXAMPLE: Transfer money between accounts

Account A: $100
Account B: $50

Operation 1: Debit $20 from A → A: $80
Operation 2: Credit $20 to B → B: $70

If Operation 1 succeeds but Operation 2 fails:
A: $80 (debited)
B: $50 (not credited) ❌ INCONSISTENT

With Transaction:
Both operations succeed → A: $80, B: $70 ✓
Or both fail → A: $100, B: $50 ✓

MONGODB SYNTAX:
session = db.startSession()
session.startTransaction()

try {
  db.accounts.updateOne({_id: "A"}, {$inc: {balance: -20}}, {session})
  db.accounts.updateOne({_id: "B"}, {$inc: {balance: +20}}, {session})
  session.commitTransaction()
} catch (error) {
  session.abortTransaction()
}
finally {
  session.endSession()
}

16. AGGREGATION FRAMEWORK
What is Aggregation?
AGGREGATION = Process data through pipeline stages

EXAMPLE: Get average age by country

Data:
{ country: "USA", age: 25, name: "Alice" }
{ country: "USA", age: 30, name: "Bob" }
{ country: "UK", age: 28, name: "Charlie" }
{ country: "UK", age: 32, name: "Diana" }

Pipeline:
Stage 1: $match → Filter countries
Stage 2: $group → Group by country, calculate average
Stage 3: $sort → Sort results

Result:
{ _id: "UK", avgAge: 30 }
{ _id: "USA", avgAge: 27.5 }

MONGODB SYNTAX:
db.users.aggregate([
  {
    $match: { age: { $gte: 25 } }
  },
  {
    $group: {
      _id: "$country",
      avgAge: { $avg: "$age" },
      count: { $sum: 1 }
    }
  },
  {
    $sort: { avgAge: -1 }
  }
])

