21. DATA DESIGN PATTERNS
Pattern 1: Embedding vs Referencing
USER WITH ADDRESSES

EMBEDDING (Store address in document):
{
  _id: 1,
  name: "Alice",
  addresses: [
    { street: "Main St", city: "NYC" },
    { street: "2nd Ave", city: "Boston" }
  ]
}

Pros: ✓ Single query
Cons: ✗ Duplication if shared

REFERENCING (Store reference):
Users:
{ _id: 1, name: "Alice" }

Addresses:
{ _id: 101, user_id: 1, street: "Main St", city: "NYC" }
{ _id: 102, user_id: 1, street: "2nd Ave", city: "Boston" }

Pros: ✓ No duplication
Cons: ✗ Multiple queries

RULE:
One-to-Few → Embed
One-to-Many → Separate (reference)
One-to-Millions → Definitely separate

Pattern 2: One-to-One Relationship
User has one profile

OPTION 1: Embed in same document
{
  _id: 1,
  name: "Alice",
  email: "alice@test.com",
  profile: {
    bio: "Developer",
    followers: 1000,
    verified: true
  }
}

OPTION 2: Separate documents
Users: { _id: 1, name: "Alice", email: "..." }
Profiles: { _id: 1, user_id: 1, bio: "...", followers: 1000 }

Pattern 3: One-to-Many Relationship
User has many posts

Posts Collection:
[
  { _id: 101, user_id: 1, title: "Post 1" },
  { _id: 102, user_id: 1, title: "Post 2" },
  { _id: 103, user_id: 2, title: "Post 3" }
]

Query: Get all posts by Alice (user_id: 1)
db.posts.find({ user_id: 1 })

Good for: Posts, Comments, Orders, etc.

22. QUERY EXAMPLES
MongoDB Query Examples
FIND ALL:
db.users.find()

FIND WITH FILTER:
db.users.find({ age: { $gt: 25 } })
// age greater than 25

FIND WITH AND:
db.users.find({ age: { $gt: 25 }, country: "USA" })
// age > 25 AND country = USA

FIND WITH OR:
db.users.find({ $or: [ { age: { $gt: 50 } }, { country: "UK" } ] })
// age > 50 OR country = UK

FIND AND PROJECT (select fields):
db.users.find({ }, { name: 1, email: 1, _id: 0 })
// Return only name and email

FIND WITH SORT:
db.users.find().sort({ age: -1 })
// Sort by age descending

FIND WITH LIMIT:
db.users.find().limit(10)
// Get first 10 documents

FIND WITH SKIP:
db.users.find().skip(20).limit(10)
// Skip first 20, get next 10 (pagination)

23. INDEXING IN NOSQL
Creating Indexes
CREATE SIMPLE INDEX:
db.users.createIndex({ email: 1 })

Query becomes faster:
db.users.find({ email: "alice@test.com" })

CREATE COMPOUND INDEX:
db.users.createIndex({ country: 1, city: 1 })

Query becomes faster:
db.users.find({ country: "USA", city: "NYC" })

CREATE TEXT INDEX:
db.articles.createIndex({ content: "text" })

Query becomes faster:
db.articles.find({ $text: { $search: "mongodb" } })

CREATE GEOSPATIAL INDEX:
db.stores.createIndex({ location: "2dsphere" })

Query becomes faster:
db.stores.find({
  location: {
    $near: { type: "Point", coordinates: [ -73.9667, 40.78 ] }
  }
})

